metadata.name: {Lumina} #1508
metadata.description:
The restitution of a breath
Your breath is your artwork

{Lumina} is part of the installation Σ Lumina taking place at Musée d’Orsay. A free live minting is scheduled from February 13th to March 10th, 2024. 

Breath, the vital essence, embodies our interconnection. It carries our shared heritage. A medium that helps Σ Lumina to unite the physical and the digital, the living with the coded. The voices of Orsay resonate within us, their breath becoming ours, landscaping our common creation.

metadata.name: One Point Five Degrees Celcius #5
metadata.description:
One Point Five Degrees Celcius features 128 quotes from the infamous IPCC Report on the consequences of Global Warming of 1.5°C. 

The science on the climate crisis is very clear and succinct. We need to act or all of our lives will be forever changed for the worse. Yet politicians, companies and other entities in power continue to mislead, lie and downplay the crisis. 

To symbolize these issues, each edition features one quote, surrounded by unique chaotic shapes, colors and glitchy effects, all attempting to distract from the clear scientific conclusions.

This project scales to fit your screen, so I recommend trying it out on different devices and in different modes. 

· Interactions ·

Double-click: Read the quote out loud using text-to-speech. May not be supported on all devices. 

Swipe left/right or left/right arrow key: Show the previous/next quote on the list.

· Contributions and license ·

2.5% of the primary sales will go towards supporting the Trans Education Network of Texas.

This project is made with p5.js, FettePalette and the font Inter by Rasmus Andersson.

This project is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: Mindset #51
metadata.description:
Creating concepts implies creating limits in the continuous. 
Definitions are necessary to communicate. 
Boundaries have to be set to be broken.
Beliefs define our ego but not our essence.
Aren't we the invisible structure that can perceive itself under its own construct?

metadata.name: Klyft #903
metadata.description:
“Klyft” is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.

Klyft is a juxtaposition of two different projections for the future. One, made by the World Economic Forum, suggests that the global gender gap will have closed by the year 2154. The other, by the UN IPCC, estimates that global warming will reach 3.2 degrees celcius by the year 2100.

Klyft makes use of the unique temporal aspect of computational art by developing its expression gradually over the next 132 years. As we come closer to 2154, the space between the two shapes in Klyft will grow smaller to symbolize the closing of the gender gap. As time goes on, however, Klyft also becomes more and more glitched out to represent the projected increases in greenhouse gases and climate catastrophes.

In the end, Klyft’s expression will be heavily corrupted, and the two shapes will have reached each other.

· URL parameters ·

You can add the following parameters to the URL to change the behavior of the piece.

date=<YYYY-MM-DD> — See how Klyft looks on another day. Use the format YYYY-MM-DD. 

color=<number> — See the piece in another color scheme. The numbers loop around, so 17 equals 0, 18 equals 1, etc. 

resolution=<number> — View the piece in a higher resolution. 1 is normal resolution, 2 is double, etc. No decimals allowed.

image=true — Save the piece as an image. 

record=true — Save the piece as a video in WEBM format.

Adding the following URL parameters will show Klyft in double resolution on the day gender equality is achieved according to the WEF:

date=2154-01-01&resolution=2

Adding the following URL parameters will save a video of Klyft in the ‘Stokkendahl Dalgas’ color scheme:

color=14&record=true

· Interactions ·

Pressing the following keys will trigger functionality as well as add related URL parameters automatically. 

Pressing D will increment the date by 1 year.

Pressing C will increment the color index by 1.

Pressing R will toggle between normal and double resolution.

Pressing I will toggle the image URL parameter, which saves the piece as an image. Only works outside of iframe.

Pressing V will toggle the video URL parameter, which saves the piece as a video. Only works outside of iframe.

There are secret key presses as well. Some of them only work outside of iframe. 

· Accessibility ·

Klyft is built to support screen readers. It has been tested using MacOS’ VoiceOver, and uses p5.js’ describeElement() to provide screen reader functionality.

If you have any comments (good or bad) on the screen reader integration, don’t hesitate to reach out on my Twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art. 

· Credits and license ·

Klyft is made with p5.js.

Klyft is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: Rhythms #511
metadata.description:
"Routines, patterns, cadence.
Events, turns, chaos.
Predictable lives,
split-second dramas."

This project is inspired by the delicate balance between daily habits and life-turning points.
There's structure in the flow. There's awe in the silence.

"Rhythms" invites you to reflect on the beautiful complexity that fills our vital experience, on the millions of tiny details that bring texture to our journey causing balance or disruption.

-

Key Features:
- 12 color palettes: Determines colors used on the artwork
- 3 Orientation modes (square, portrait, landscape): Portrait and landscape are rare
- 6 Alignment Types: Determines lines' distribution pattern

Secondary features provide additional variation.

Enter live mode and press "s" to download high resolution image ( 5940x5940 px ).

-

50% of secondary market royalties go to minters.
Coded in p5js, with love.

metadata.name: Little Trees #244
metadata.description:
Delicate, little trees. Some with green leaves, some with orange, some with red. This is the genesis project of Brian Gawlik.

The default resolution is 3600x3600. To redraw and save as an image at a different resolution - in the live view, open your browser's devtools and execute the function saveImg(pixWidth) where pixWidth is the desired width in pixels of the image. For example, saveImg(4096) will prompt you to download a 4096x4096 image. It is recommended not to export below 2400x2400 as this will compromise the aesthetic of the shadow.

metadata.name: Citadels, At night. #19
metadata.description:
Citadels, at night is a passion project started short after my Space Anomalies collection. It's inspired by the movement of noise fields and the feeling of space and height you feel often when looking at citadels.

Hoping to bring some joy and beauty with this piece.

----

You can click to save a 5000x5000 image of your citadel.


Made by Wouter Missler with p5js.
